data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### Pattern Analysis

Your code contains **four** patterns that must be migrated:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeps thread alive after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and decide |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` may block | Pass `CancellationToken` so blocked call can wake up |

### Key Pitfalls for This Code

1. **`GetNextItem()` may block** — `Thread.Abort()` could interrupt this on .NET Framework, but `CancellationToken` will **not** interrupt it unless `GetNextItem` is modified to accept and honor the token. This is the most critical change.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` kept the loop alive** — In the migrated version, cancellation of a single item doesn't kill the loop. Use a per-item `CancellationTokenSource` linked to the main token.
3. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` in `Stop()`** — Replace with `Thread.Join(timeout)` which actually waits for the thread, rather than blindly sleeping.
4. **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** — Wrap in a `using` or dispose in `Stop()`.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token))
        {
            IsBackground = true
        };
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Per-item CTS linked to the main token. This replaces the
            // ResetAbort pattern: cancelling a single item doesn't stop
            // the loop, but cancelling the main token stops everything.
            using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(itemCts.Token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Only the per-item token was cancelled (not the main token).
                // This is the equivalent of the old ResetAbort path:
                // clean up partial work and continue the loop.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Main token was cancelled — we're shutting down.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully.
        // Thread.Join(timeout) is better than Thread.Sleep — it
        // actually waits for the thread rather than blindly sleeping.
        if (_workerThread is { IsAlive: true })
            _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, the thread is stuck in
        // uncooperative code. Log a warning — there is no safe
        // equivalent to Thread.Abort in modern .NET.
        if (_workerThread is { IsAlive: true })
            LogWarning("Worker thread did not stop within timeout.");
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What Must Also Change

**`GetNextItem` must accept and honor the token.** If it blocks on a queue, use a cancellation-aware collection:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — Thread.Abort could interrupt this
private object GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Dequeue(); // blocks forever if empty
}

// After (.NET 8) — cooperative cancellation
private object GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // BlockingCollection<T>.Take natively supports CancellationToken
    return _blockingCollection.Take(token);

    // Or if using Channel<T> (preferred in modern .NET):
    // return _channel.Reader.ReadAsync(token).AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult();
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls synchronous I/O that **cannot** accept a token (e.g., raw `socket.Receive`), you must either switch to async I/O (`await socket.ReceiveAsync(buffer, token)`) or, as a last resort, isolate the work in a child process and use `Process.Kill`.

### Summary of All Removed APIs

| Removed | Replacement in migrated code |
|---------|------------------------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter + continue loop |
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` in Stop | `Thread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` |

The critical mental model shift: **cancellation is now cooperative**. Nothing can forcibly stop a thread — `GetNextItem` and `ProcessItem` must check the token at regular intervals or pass it to blocking APIs, or the thread will not stop.
